  # Create the MongoDB Search Index

  ## Step 1: Connect to your cluster using .

  Open [Compass](https://www.mongodb.com/try/download/compass) and connect to your cluster. For
  detailed instructions, see [Compass](atlas-connect-via-compass).

  ## Step 2: Specify the database and collection.

  On the Database screen, click the name of the database, then click the name of the collection.

  ## Step 3: Create the  index.

  - Click the Indexes tab, then select Search Indexes.

  - Click Create Atlas Search Index to open the index creation dialog box.

  - Name the index, `embedded-documents-tutorial`.

  - Specify the JSON (Javascript Object Notation) MongoDB Search index definition.

    ```json
    {
      "mappings": {
        "dynamic": true,
        "fields": {
          "clubs": {
            "dynamic": true,
            "fields": {
              "sports": {
                "dynamic": true,
                "type": "embeddedDocuments"
              }
            },
            "type": "document"
          },
          "teachers": [
            {
              "dynamic": true,
              "fields": {
                "classes": {
                  "dynamic": true,
                  "type": "embeddedDocuments"
                }
              },
              "type": "embeddedDocuments"
            },
            {
              "dynamic": true,
              "fields": {
                "classes": {
                  "dynamic": true,
                  "fields": {
                    "grade": {
                      "type": "token"
                    }
                  },
                  "type": "document"
                }
              },
              "type": "document"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    }
    ```

  - Click Create Search Index.

  # Run `$search` Queries Against Embedded Document Fields

  You can run queries against the embedded document fields. This
  tutorial uses [embeddedDocument](embedded-document-ref) and [text](text-ref)
  operators inside the [compound](compound-ref) operator in the queries.

  In this section, you will connect to your cluster and run
  the sample queries using the operators against the fields in the
  `schools` collection.

  ## Step 1: Connect to your cluster in .

  Open MongoDB Compass and connect to your cluster. For detailed
  instructions on connecting, see [Compass](atlas-connect-via-compass).

  ## Step 2: Use the  collection in the  database.

  On the Database screen, click the
  `local_school_district` database, and then click the `schools`
  collection.

  ## Step 3: Run the following  queries against the  collection.

  To learn more about these queries, see [query](embedded-documents-tutorial-queries).

  <Tab tabid="basic">
    Nested Array

    To learn more about this query, see [query](embedded-documents-tutorial-queries).

    | Pipeline Stage | Query                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  |
    | -------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
    | $search        | \{ "index": "embedded-documents-tutorial", "embeddedDocument": \{ "path": "teachers", "operator": \{ "compound": \{ "must": \[\{ "text": \{ "path": "teachers.first", "query": "John" } }], "should":\[\{ "text": \{ "path": "teachers.last", "query": "Smith" } }] } } }, "highlight": \{ "path": "teachers.last" } } |
    | $project       | \{ "\_id": 1, "teachers": 1, "score": \{ $meta: "searchScore" }, "highlights": \{ "$meta": "searchHighlights" } }If you enabled Auto Preview, MongoDB Compass displays the following documents next to the $project pipeline stage:                                                                                    |

    ```shell
    [
      {
        _id: 1,
        teachers: [
          {
            first: 'Jane',
            last: 'Earwhacker',
            classes: [
              { subject: 'art', grade: '9th' },
              { subject: 'science', grade: '12th' }
            ]
          },
          {
            first: 'John',
            last: 'Smith',
            classes: [
              { subject: 'math', grade: '12th' },
              { subject: 'art', grade: '10th' }
            ]
          }
        ],
        score: 0.7830756902694702,
        highlights: [
          {
            score: 1.4921371936798096,
            path: 'teachers.last',
            texts: [ { value: 'Smith', type: 'hit' } ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        _id: 2,
        teachers: [
          {
            first: 'Jane',
            last: 'Smith',
            classes: [
              { subject: 'science', grade: '9th' },
              { subject: 'math', grade: '12th' }
            ]
          },
          {
            first: 'John',
            last: 'Redman',
            classes: [ { subject: 'art', grade: '12th' } ]
          }
        ],
        score: 0.468008816242218,
        highlights: [
          {
            score: 1.4702850580215454,
            path: 'teachers.last',
            texts: [ { value: 'Smith', type: 'hit' } ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
    ```

    The two documents in the results contain teachers with the first name
    `John`. The document with `_id: 1` ranks higher because it
    contains a teacher with the first name `John` who also has the last
    name `Smith`.
